Euthanized - Peritonitis  Examined cow at 9:30 am after being treated with epinephrine and flunixin meglumine at 2 and 4am. The cows was still in distress despite treatment  with elevated HR (98 bpm) and RR (72 bpm)  with continuous grunting and teeth grinding. Rectal temperature WNL. No pathological sounds detected on thoracic auscultation. No ruminal contractions detected in 2 min. Auscultation-percussion of the left and right flanks was WNL. Succussion of the abdomen on both flanks suggested free fluid in abdomen. Subcutaneous emphysema was present over the lumbar area on both sides. Cow showed signs of pain during rectal exam (i.e.  greater grunting  kicking her belly) and rectal exam was unremarkable other than the suggestion of free fluid in the abdomen. TENTATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Peritonitis. PROGNOSIS: Poor After discussion with farm assistant manager over phone  the cow was euthanized with 120 mL FatalPlus IV due to poor prognosis and welfare concerns of cow remaining in pain 4 h after medical treatment. FIELD NECROPSY: After euthanasia  a gross post-mortem examination of the abdomen was conducted. Findings were unremarkable other than abundant (> 5L) free serum-like fluid in the abdomen. No signs of hardware disease were noted.
